'''Okataka Shrine''' (おかたかじんじゃ), official name: Okataka Shrine, is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} enshrined in Kitanogō-chō, {{ill|lt=Nagahama|Q844130|WD=Q844130|1=Nagahama, Shiga}}, {{ill|lt=Shiga Prefecture|Q131358|WD=Q131358|1=Shiga Prefecture}}.

===Enshrined deities===
It enshrines {{ill|lt=Sugawara no Michizane|Q382005|WD=Q382005|lt=Sugawara no Michizane-kō|1=Sugawara no Michizane}} (すがわらみちざねこう) and {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|WD=Q272993|lt=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}}.

===Shrine crest===
Star-plum-bowl crest

===History===
In year 3 of {{ill|lt=Emperor Yūryaku|Q357235|WD=Q357235|1=Emperor Yūryaku}} ({{ill|lt=459|Q30500|WD=Q30500|1=459}}), {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Gamō no Inagi Samamaro|1=UNKNOWN}} first enshrined {{ill|lt=Susanoo|Q272993|WD=Q272993|lt=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto}} on Senjōo-dake, 2 km east of the current site; in {{ill|lt=Hakuhō|Q11580612|WD=Q11580612|1=Hakuhō}} 13 ({{ill|lt=685|Q33480|WD=Q33480|1=685}}), it was moved to the current otabisho. In {{ill|lt=Ninju|Q1373077|WD=Q1373077|1=Ninju}} 1 ({{ill|lt=851|Q29966|WD=Q29966|1=851}}), {{ill|lt=Ono no Takamura|Q1139928|WD=Q1139928|1=Ono no Takamura}} built shrine buildings at the current site and called it Okamoto Shrine. At that time this area was Okamoto-gō of Asai District. During syncretic times, there was {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Okatakayama Jingū-ji|1=UNKNOWN}}. In the Sengoku period, clergy avoided {{ill|lt=Oda Nobunaga|Q171411|WD=Q171411|1=Oda Nobunaga}}’s temple-shrine burnings by inviting from Kyoto’s {{ill|lt=Kitano Tenmangū|Q662176|WD=Q662176|1=Kitano Tenmangū}}, having heard that his father Nobuhide revered {{ill|lt=Tenmangū|Q798838|WD=Q798838|1=Tenmangū}}, and called it Okataka Tenjin.
From early Meiji it became Okataka Shrine; in {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 9 ({{ill|lt=1876|Q7766|WD=Q7766|1=1876}}) it became {{ill|lt=village shrine|Q134917284|WD=Q134917284|1=Son-sha}}, and in Meiji 17 ({{ill|lt=1884|Q7819|WD=Q7819|1=1884}}) it became {{ill|lt=gōsha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}.

As the sōsha of 15 villages of Shimokusano-shō, it was deeply revered. In droughts, rain prayers were held, choosing among taiko dance, yuno-hana, and tōmyō rites; when prayers were fulfilled, a thanksgiving taiko dance by all 15 villages was dedicated. This rain-prayer custom continued until before the war; now it has ceased, with three taiko dance preservation groups remaining.

The main sanctuary was built in {{ill|lt=Shōtoku (Japan)|Q1193848|WD=Q1193848|lt=Shōtoku|1=Shōtoku (era)}} 6 ({{ill|lt=1716|Q6892|WD=Q6892|1=1716}}) by Ubahuchi Jirosuke (Kaodo Village) as nagare-zukuri with chidori-karahafu. The worship hall was completed in Meiji 21 by master builder {{ill|lt=Itō Heizaemon IX|Q17193360|WD=Q17193360|lt=Itō Heizaemon Morimichi|1=Itō Heizaemon IX}} of {{ill|lt=Nagoya|Q11751|WD=Q11751|1=Nagoya}} as an irimoyao-zukuri, cypress-bark roof, 4-ken frontage by 3-ken depth.
The middle gate and corridor fence were built in {{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|WD=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1930|Q18787|WD=Q18787|1=1930}}), and the shrine office was rebuilt in {{ill|lt=Heisei|Q234510|WD=Q234510|1=Heisei era}} 3 ({{ill|lt=1991|Q2062|WD=Q2062|1=1991}}) as an imperial enthronement commemorative project.

=== Festivals ===
* Annual festival: Saturday/Sunday nearest {{ill|lt=April 25|Q2531|WD=Q2531|1=April 25}}
* Tōmyō Festival: {{ill|lt=August 25|Q2819|WD=Q2819|1=August 25}}

=== Shrine treasures ===
